\details{
\subsection{Generating the OCULUS search spreadsheet}{

The \code{search_xlsx} file is an Excel export from the FDEP OCULUS public
document portal.  To generate it:
\enumerate{
\item Navigate to \url{https://depedms.dep.state.fl.us} in a web browser.
\item Click \strong{Public Oculus Login} (no account required).
\item In the search form, set:
\itemize{
\item \strong{Catalog}: Wastewater
\item \strong{Profile}: Sampling
\item \strong{Facility-Site ID}: FLA012124 (not the Permit Number field)
\item \strong{Document Date}: From MM-DD-YYYY to MM-DD-YYYY (covering the desired year)
\item \strong{Document Type}: Discharge Monitoring Report (DMR)
}
\item Run the search and export the results to Excel (\strong{Export to Excel} button).
\item Save the exported \code{.xlsx} and pass its path as \code{search_xlsx}.
}

The file must contain \code{HYPERLINK()} formulas in \strong{column A} and document
subject lines in \strong{column K}, both of which are present in any standard
OCULUS search export.
}

\subsection{Document selection and classification}{

All monthly (\code{MO}) documents for the requested year are downloaded and
inspected.  Each PDF is then classified by its actual content:
\itemize{
\item \strong{Part A} (monthly summary) -- contains the official permit-limit table
with pre-computed monthly averages and permit compliance results.
\item \strong{Part B} (daily sample results) -- contains a day-by-day table of flow
and effluent quality measurements for a given month.
}

The OCULUS document labels ("Part A", "Part B") are not always reliable for
this facility, so the function detects content type from the PDF text.  Annual
summary (\code{YR}) documents are excluded automatically.

Some older submissions are scanned image PDFs with no embedded text layer.
These cannot be parsed and are saved as
\verb{macdill_unclassified_\{document_subject\}.pdf} in \code{pdf_dir} (when
\code{pdf_dir} is supplied) so you can identify them from their OCULUS subject
line and enter the values manually if needed.
}

\subsection{Hybrid extraction methodology}{

Where a Part B daily table is available for a given calendar month, BOD and
TSS are computed as the mean of all observed daily values using the
substitution rules \verb{<1 \\u\{2192\} 0.5} and \verb{<2 \\u\{2192\} 1.0} (consistent with the
2022--2024 reporting methodology).  Monthly average flow is also derived from
Part B daily readings when available.  For months with no Part B, Part A
monthly-summary values are used for BOD, TSS, and flow.

Total nitrogen (\code{tn_mgl}) is sourced from Part B page 2 (column 00620,
biweekly readings averaged) when available, falling back to the Part A
monthly maximum when no Part B is present.
}

\subsection{Monitoring period vs. OCULUS label}{

The OCULUS document cycle labels (e.g., "JAN MO") do not always align with
the calendar month of the monitoring period.  The \code{mo} column in the output
is always derived from the monitoring period dates inside the PDF, not
from the OCULUS label.
}

\subsection{No Discharge (NOD) and acceptable non-collection (ANC)}{

\code{NOD} (No Observable Discharge) is treated as zero flow and \code{NA}
concentration.  \code{ANC} (Acceptable Not Collected) is treated as \code{NA}.
}
}
